  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Towards an AIDS free generation (TAFU)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">3500 Families in the target districts are socially and economically empowered;  Communities in the 5 target districts (12 subcounties) are knowledgeable  of the specific needs of children living with HIV and mobilized to support the target families; improved systems for tracing, referral and follow-up by VHTs and HCWs in 17 health centres catch areas</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Uganda 193,500 children under 14 years old are estimated to be living with HIV. More than half of these children are not yet on care. More over 43 infants continue to be born with HIV every day.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The overall goal of this project is:
&#x2022; to reduce the number of new HIV infections among infants and increase the number of HIV-positive children on treatment in the target districts. 

The specific objectives are to: 
&#x2022; improve uptake and retention of HIV-positive mothers and exposed infants in PMTCT-care;
&#x2022; increase the number of children tested (both infants and children up to 14);
&#x2022; increase access to and retention in life-long care and treatment for HIV-positive children.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to reduce the number of new HIV infections among children, and to increase the number of children living with HIV who receive antiretroviral therapy (ART). To realise this, we are improving the social and economic position of 3.500 families (10,000 children living with HIV) in three regions in Uganda. In addition, we are educating people to improve support mechanisms within the communities. Most importantly, the project contributes to improved collaboration between clinics and communities, and thus better tracing, referral and follow-up mechanisms.</narrative>
  </description>
